Haarlem, North Holland, Netherlands":"Haarlem, North Holland, Netherlands","Wesel, Wesel, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany":"Wesel, Wesel, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany","Gelderland, Netherlands":"Gelderland, Netherlands","Leuwarden,Friesland, Netherlands":"Friesland, Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Janz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Armin, Franz, Guenter, Siegfried.","German: patronymic from the personal name   Jan   1. Compare   Johnson  .","Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Janc</b>: nickname from a vernacular spelling of <i>janjec</i> ‘lamb’, or a patronymic from (a short form of) the personal name <i>Janez</i>, an equivalent of   John  . Compare   Jantz   2 and   Yantz   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Janzer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","North German: derivative of   Janz  ."]},{"name":"Jan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammad, Mohammed, Ferdous, Momin, Sultan, Ahmad, Altaf, Ameen, Amin, Amina, Arif, Arshad.  French Pierre, Andre, Marcel, Pascale.","North German, Danish, Polish, Sorbian, and Croatian; Czech (also <b>Ján</b>); Slovak (<b>Ján</b>): from the personal name <i>Jan</i> (Slovak <i>Ján</i>), a shortened vernacular form of Latin <i>Johannes</i> (see   John  ). The Sorbian surname is found mainly in Germanized forms,   Jahn   and <b>Jähn</b>. See also   Yan  .","Slovenian: from the personal name <i>Jan</i>, a variant or a short form of <i>Janez</i>, an equivalent of   John  ."]},{"name":"Jantz","meanings":["German: variant of   Janz   1, a patronymic from the personal name   Jan   1.","Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Janc</b> (see   Janz   2)."]}]},{"name":"Margaretha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margarethe","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"Maria","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Maria  , of German origin but now also moderately popular in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356704,"age":1,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"description":"Britain waged wars against the Dutch.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356705,"age":3,"year":"1602","julianDay":2306179,"description":"\"The United East India Company (V.O.C.), destined to become a powerful force in Holland's \"\"Golden Age\"\"of discovery, exploration, and trade, is founded.\"","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1356710,"age":25,"year":"1624","julianDay":2314214,"description":"The Dutch conquered Salvador, Brazil.","jurisdictionLevel":2}